04491nam a22005295i 9780226174938DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014015929  a9780226174938  a(DE-B1597)524107  a(OCoLC)894270850  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQC352b.S57 2014 7aSCI0000002bisacsh  aUH 50002rvk1 aSmith, A. Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Sight to Light :bThe Passage from Ancient to Modern Optics /cA. Mark Smith. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (480 p.) :b41 halftones, 58 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1 Introduction -- tChapter 2 The Emergence of Optics as a Science -- tChapter 3 Ptolemy and the Flowering of Greek Optics -- tChapter 4 Greco-Roman and Early Arabic Developments -- tChapter 5 Alhacen and the Grand Synthesis -- tChapter 6 Developments in the Medieval Latin West -- tChapter 7 The Assimilation of Perspectivist Optics during the Later Middle Ages and Renaissance -- tChapter 8 The Keplerian Turn and Its Technical Background -- tChapter 9 The Seventeenth- Century Response -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom its inception in Greek antiquity, the science of optics was aimed primarily at explaining sight and accounting for why things look as they do. By the end of the seventeenth century, however, the analytic focus of optics had shifted to light: its fundamental properties and such physical behaviors as reflection, refraction, and diffraction. This dramatic shift—which A. Mark Smith characterizes as the “Keplerian turn”—lies at the heart of this fascinating and pioneering study. Breaking from previous scholarship that sees Johannes Kepler as the culmination of a long-evolving optical tradition that traced back to Greek antiquity via the Muslim Middle Ages, Smith presents Kepler instead as marking a rupture with this tradition, arguing that his theory of retinal imaging, which was published in 1604, was instrumental in prompting the turn from sight to light. Kepler’s new theory of sight, Smith reveals, thus takes on true historical significance: by treating the eye as a mere light-focusing device rather than an image-producing instrument—as traditionally understood—Kepler’s account of retinal imaging helped spur the shift in analytic focus that eventually led to modern optics. A sweeping survey, From Sight to Light is poised to become the standard reference for historians of optics as well as those interested more broadly in the history of science, the history of art, and cultural and intellectual history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aOpticsxHistory. 70(DE-601)1062087210(DE-588)4043650-0aOptik2gnd 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aoptics, vision, light, reflection, refraction, diffraction, johannes kepler, antiquity, middle ages, islam, imaging, retina, sight, eye, science, art, visual ray, euclid, catoptrics, focal properties, mirrors, ptolemy, perception, illusion, moon, atmosphere, astronomy, plotinus, saint augustine, de anima, alhacen, perspectiva, cognition, aristotle, convex lenses, color, nonfiction, anatomy, biology, philosophy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022617476140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226174938423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226174938/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles